<H5>  Psychologist Cites Lack of Affection as Cause </H5>
  Psychologist Wilton Barros de Araujo of the State Institute 
for the Welfare of Minors (IEBEM), who works with "addicted" 
children in Manaus, claims that lack of affection is the main 
factor leading individuals to seek drugs. "Man needs food to 
survive, and affection feeds the spirit. If he does not find it 
in his family, he seeks escape through drugs," the psychologist 
explains. 
  Wilton Araujo says that an expression much used by drug 
addicts -- "ficar noiado" -- characterizes that lack of 
affection. "Ficar noiado" means "everything I want I get." What 
does that mean? When the addict is "noiado," he can, on his 
trips, mistreat the people who did not give him affection or 
imagine that he is being loved, among other things. He flees his 
actual reality and seeks the reality he wants." 
  The psychologist also observes that even the sensation of 
"coming down," which the individual feels when the drug wears 
off, is considered by many to be preferable to the reality of 
the world in which they live. 
  Wilton warns of the lack of competence among people working 
with addicts. He says that the few treatment centers in Amazonas 
and the rest of Brazil today employ people who are poorly paid 
and dissatisfied. "To salvage a drug addict, the institutions 
would have to create an atmosphere that he did not have at home 
and show the individual that the world is not as bad as he 
thinks it is. But with extremely rare exceptions, the treatment 
centers are unable to do that," he comments. 

